 the node ID since the data persisted on the PVC. When I patched the StatefulSet to add an init container with an emptyDir mounted at the config directory, the new pod spec rolled out and elasticsearch-0 restarted with that emptyDir replacing its config directory. My hypothesis is that the emptyDir started fresh without the elasticsearch.yml from the image, which might have caused the node to initialize differently.\n\nActually, I'm realizing the issue might be more subtle: the image's default elasticsearch.yml probably lacks `cluster.initial_master_nodes` or `discovery.seed_hosts`, so elasticsearch-0 could have done a fresh bootstrap and generated a new node ID stored in the data PVC. But if elasticsearch-2 and elasticsearch-1 had the same problem, they should have also gotten new IDs—unless the rolling update order matters. StatefulSets roll updates from highest to lowest ordinal, so elasticsearch-2 restarted first while the old cluster still had elasticsearch-0 and elasticsearch-1 with their original IDs, allowing elasticsearch-2 to rejoin with its old ID. Then elasticsearch-1 restarted with elasticsearch-0 still present in the cluster.\n\nNow I'm wondering if there's a completely different angle here—the old voting config had 5 nodes, but the elasticsearch StatefulSet only has 3 pods, so the other 2 voting nodes must be from a different StatefulSet. I need to check if the `es-seed` ConfigMap and the `es-cluster` StatefulSet are sharing the same cluster name and seed hosts configuration.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1158,"cache_read_input_tokens":98504,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1158},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"82476b60-f4cb-48ca-92a0-0e5d08c71292","uuid":"da2836b4-12c9-4b87-88