{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_011SiYyFygrJbkJ9mK7grdm1","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `es-cluster` StatefulSet uses THE SAME ConfigMap (`es-config`) and TLS certs (`es-http-tls`) as the `elasticsearch` StatefulSet. So they're in the SAME cluster!\n\nWait, but the `es-cluster` StatefulSet mounts the config differently - it mounts the whole ConfigMap (not subPath), with the key `elasticsearch.yml`. This is slightly different from the `elasticsearch` StatefulSet which uses subPath.\n\nBut regardless, both are pointing to cluster.name: elasticsearch and using the same elasticsearch.yml. So the `es-cluster` pods are in the SAME cluster as the `elasticsearch` pods.\nNow I'm thinking about the 7 nodes I saw - three from `elasticsearch`, three from `es-cluster`, and a seventh that's likely `es-transform-0` or `es-data-new`. The voting config has 5 master-eligible nodes, which is odd if all 6 pods from both StatefulSets are master-eligible. That suggests one of them isn't participating in the voting configuration.\n\nBut the real puzzle is why elasticsearch-0 has a completely different node ID now compared to before. Looking at the restart history, elasticsearch-0 had 4 restarts, and I need to figure out what triggered that 4th restart. The ConfigMap subPath mount overlays the cluster-specific elasticsearch.yml at that path, while the certs Secret provides the necessary certificates. When elasticsearch-0 finally restarts as the last node, all other nodes are already running, so it should rejoin the cluster—though its node ID will change after the restart, which might cause issues with the voting configuration that still references the old ID. The issue might be that when elasticsearch-0 can't join the cluster due to lack of quorum, it bootstraps a new cluster instead of waiting—but only if the data directory is clean. Since the data PVC should persist, the real culprit could be that the init container is copying the image's default elasticsearch.yml to the config emptyDir, which might have different settings than what I configured.\n\nLet me check what's actually in elasticsearch-0's data directory and what node ID it's using to understand the cluster state better.\n\nActually, I should try a different approach to fix this without needing to understand the root cause. I could bootstrap the cluster fresh using the `elasticsearch-node` tool, which would lose the cluster state but get things running again—and since this is a test cluster with no critical data, that's acceptable. Alternatively, I could try adding elasticsearch-0's new node ID to the voting configuration, though that requires the cluster to be up first. Or I could remove the three dead node IDs from the voting config directly on disk using the `elasticsearch-node` tool, which would need me to exec into a pod.\n\nLet me check if the existing es-cluster pods might already have node IDs that are in the voting config—if three of them match, they could form a quorum and bootstrap themselves. Looking at the voting config again: [D4YW3dRDQZSNug9qD7JdPw, 07En9A76R96QWjBqCEzp2Q, RS4egGB_TV2xW_Ts6IV7gA, jfCekqKZRlKnySj8zb_LqA, IXzfWXW-RLSqu9wDxl6GbQ], and comparing it against the node IDs I found earlier...\n\nFive of the seven nodes are actually in the voting config, while the other two aren't. Those two non-voting nodes might be the data-only es-cluster nodes, which would explain why they're not part of the quorum.\n\nLooking at the pod counts more carefully: the elasticsearch StatefulSet has 3 pods and es-cluster has 3 pods, giving 6 total node IDs. Since only 5 are in the voting config, that means 1 is configured as data-only. After restarting the elasticsearch StatefulSet, I'm seeing elasticsearch-0 got a new node ID that's not in the old voting config, while elasticsearch-1 and elasticsearch-2 retained their original IDs that are in the voting config.\n\nThe es-cluster pods are still running with unchanged node IDs, but the discovery mechanism isn't finding them because the elasticsearch.yml seed hosts only point to the elasticsearch headless service, not the es-cluster service. So even though some es-cluster nodes might be in the voting config, they're not being discovered by the elasticsearch pods initially.\n\nAfter a restart though, nodes can reconstruct the cluster state from disk and contact all known nodes beyond just the seed hosts. Let me step back and check the current state from the es-cluster pods' perspective instead, since they haven't been restarted yet.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":6066,"cache_read_input_tokens":99662,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":6066},"output_tokens":28,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"82476b60-f4cb-48ca-92a0-0e5d08c71292","uuid":"ddc2970a-d573-429e-b326-992b869374a9","request_id":"req_011CcQiHgZ2sK6TCVudjRaSn"}
