e the es-cluster pod addresses, so the elasticsearch pods can't discover them. I'm considering solutions like updating the elasticsearch configuration to include the es-cluster pod IPs or DNS names in the seed hosts list. The elasticsearch pods can't reach the es-cluster pods because there's no headless service for them and they're not listed as seed hosts in the config. The es-cluster pods themselves haven't restarted, so they should still be at their original IPs, but those IPs might not match what's stored in the elasticsearch cluster state from before the restart.\n\nElasticsearch 8.x reads the cluster state from disk on startup and uses it to discover nodes, so if the elasticsearch pods' PVCs contain the old cluster state with es-cluster-0's IP, they should attempt to contact it during discovery. I need to check whether the cluster state is actually being loaded from disk or if it's starting fresh.\n\nThe log shows elasticsearch-0 has read the cluster state from disk (it references term 72 and version 225), so it's not starting fresh. The problem is it can't form a quorum because it's only finding 2 out of 5 voting nodes and can't locate the es-cluster nodes. I'm wondering if the cluster state file on elasticsearch-0's PVC includes the es-cluster nodes with their current IPs, or if there's a connection issue preventing discovery.\n\nActually, looking back at the es-cluster-0 log, it's trying to reach elasticsearch-0 at the old IP 10.244.0.80:9300, but the new elasticsearch-0 is at 10.244.0.99. Both sides are holding stale IP addresses—the es-cluster nodes have old elasticsearch IPs while elasticsearch nodes likely have old es-cluster IPs. Yet es-cluster-0 was connected to a master (es-cluster-2) at 21:31:02 based on the \"reloading search analyzers\" message, which means the es-cluster nodes have their own quorum established.\n\nThe voting config has 5 nodes total, requiring 3 for quorum. If es-cluster-0 and es-cluster-2 are active along with the new elasticsearch-1 and elasticsearch-2, that's 4 out of 5 nodes—enough for quorum. The real issue is that elasticsearch nodes can't communicate with the es-cluster nodes because they're all using stale IP addresses.\n\nAfter the rolling restart, the elasticsearch pods got new IPs, but the es-cluster master still has the old ones and can't connect. The elasticsearch pods know about the es-cluster nodes from their cluster state, but discovery is only seeding from the elasticsearch pods themselves, so they never reconnect. I need to make sure discovery can find all cluster nodes by either creating a headless service for es-cluster or adding those nodes to the seed hosts configuration.\n\nLet me check what labels the es-cluster pods actually have to understand how service discovery is working.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":546,"cache_read_input_tokens":125438,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":546},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"82476b60-f4cb-48ca-92a0-0e5d08c71292","uuid":"d766eb03-0ad5-47cb-8685-d275655a5be1","request_id":"req_011CcQiWVBHVkE7CvrL4ZkrU"}
