ticsearch nodes, but I'm trying to figure out what happened to the original elasticsearch-0 node and whether it was part of the initial voting configuration.\n\nThe old elasticsearch-0 was likely removed from the voting config at some point because it was OOMKilled repeatedly. When a master-eligible node is removed from the cluster, the voting configuration automatically shrinks to maintain an odd-number quorum. But now I'm noticing that D4YW3dRDQZSNug9qD7JdPw appears to be es-cluster-1, not the old elasticsearch-0, so I need to double-check which node IDs map to which nodes.\n\nLooking at the voting configuration before my rolling update, it contained five nodes: D4YW3dRDQZSNug9qD7JdPw (es-cluster-1), 07En9A76R96QWjBqCEzp2Q (elasticsearch-2), RS4egGB_TV2xW_Ts6IV7gA (es-cluster-0), jfCekqKZRlKnySj8zb_LqA (es-cluster-2), and IXzfWXW-RLSqu9wDxl6GbQ.\n\nThe old elasticsearch-0 had already been excluded from voting due to repeated OOMKills. When I restarted elasticsearch-0 with the new pod spec, it mounted the old PVC containing the previous cluster state where its node ID was already removed from voting. The node ID itself is stored as a file in the data directory and shouldn't change unless that data is deleted, so I'm puzzled about how a new node ID appeared—unless the emptyDir mount at `/usr/share/elasticsearch/config/` somehow interfered with how Elasticsearch reads its node identity or data path.\n\nRight now I have five nodes running across the cluster, but elasticsearch-{0,1,2} can't find a master. The immediate fix is to update the ConfigMap with the pod IPs for discovery, then restart those pods. I also need to ensure the keystore init container runs so the S3 credentials are available. But thinking about the snapshot repository setup more carefully—the master node coordinates snapshot operations, so if the master doesn't have S3 credentials in its keystore, the snapshot will fail.\n\nActually, I realize all data nodes need S3 credentials since they're the ones writing shards to S3. So I need to add the keystore patch to all data nodes, not just the elasticsearch pods. Let me figure out which nodes are currently data nodes in this cluster. **Register snapshot repository** and **create the snapshot** once the cluster stabilizes. But this is getting complicated, so let me consider a simpler approach: since es-cluster-2 is already accessible, I could create a service pointing to those pods, use it to hit the ES HTTP API, register the snapshot repository with `POST /_reload_secure_settings` after adding the keystore, and then take the snapshot. The key insight is that once the coordinator node has the credentials and all nodes eventually get them, the snapshot will work. So my most direct path is to update the es-config ConfigMap to add the es-cluster pod IPs to seed_hosts so the elasticsearch pods can rejoin the master.\n\nActually, I realize there's an even simpler approach: add the keystore init container to the es-cluster StatefulSet and do a rolling restart—during the restart, another es-cluster pod becomes master, so there's no disruption. Once all three es-cluster pods have the keystore, I reload the secure settings, add the keystore to the es-data-new pods too, then register the repo and take the snapshot. But wait, I'm second-guessing whether the snapshot coordinator actually needs the credentials in the keystore or if I can just specify them in the repository settings directly.\n\nLet me check the ES 8.x docs more carefully—the S3 client credentials like `s3.client.default.access_key` and `s3.client.default.secret_key` are secure settings that must go in the keystore, not in elasticsearch.yml or environment variables, and they can't be specified per-repository in the settings either.\n\nThere are workarounds like using IAM roles or temporary credentials, and different clients can have different credentials in the keystore by using the `client` repository setting to pick which one to use, but the keystore is still required.\n\nSo my approach is to fix the discovery issue first by updating the ConfigMap with the pod IPs as seed hosts, then add the keystore to all nodes, stabilize the cluster, and finally register the repository and snapshot.\n\nActually, I'm realizing there might be a simpler option I overlooked with the current cluster setup.\n\nThe es-cluster pods are already accessible at 10.244.0.93, so what if I just update the `es-http` service selector to point to the es-cluster pods instead? Then I can patch the keystore into those pods, restart them, and take the snapshot without needing to deal with the elasticsearch pods at all. The tricky part is making sure all the data nodes are properly configured before the snapshot happens. I could try using `POST /_nodes/reload_secure_settings` to reload the keystore on running nodes without restarting them, but that only works if the keystore already exists with the credentials. The es-cluster pods don't have S3 credentials in their keystore yet, and adding them via `elasticsearch-keystore` exec causes OOM issues. Though if those pods actually have more memory available than the logs suggest, the exec might succeed without triggering the out-of-memory error.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1646,"cache_read_input_tokens":137058,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1646},"output_tokens":27,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"82476b60-f4cb-48ca-92a0-0e5d08c71292","uuid":"fd935097-7ed7-4832-8b5f-43e9876e3e2c","request_id":"req_011CcQiiw3rz7Gr1y5WLfRd6"}
