{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_019zXVqVMoMC2EnhTAT9eAeh","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The `_reload_secure_settings` was called but it only reached 3 nodes (es-cluster-{0,1,2}). The es-data-new nodes haven't restarted with the keystore yet (their rollout is still in progress). Also, the new es-data-new pods won't need `reload_secure_settings` since they start fresh with the keystore from the init container.\n\nWait, I see total:3, successful:3, failed:0. That's only 3 nodes (the es-cluster ones). The es-data-new nodes aren't in the cluster anymore (they're being rolled out).\nI need to fix the elasticsearch discovery issue while the rollout continues. I'll update the es-config ConfigMap to add the es-cluster pod IPs to seed_hosts and remove the cluster.initial_master_nodes setting, then restart the pods so they can properly discover each other.\n\nActually, I'm reconsidering whether to remove cluster.initial_master_nodes. In Elasticsearch 8.x, when a node without cluster state joins and finds an existing master through seed hosts, it automatically joins that existing cluster rather than bootstrapping fresh. The initial_master_nodes setting only matters when there's no existing master to connect to, so I can safely keep it and add the seed hosts—elasticsearch-0 will find the existing cluster and join it.\n\nBut there's a catch: the current error suggests elasticsearch-0 is trying to elect a master rather than join one, which means it's not discovering the existing master. This is likely because the seed hosts only point to elasticsearch-{0,1,2}, and those three nodes can't reach each other's cluster state to form a quorum. If I add the es-cluster IPs to seed_hosts, elasticsearch-0 would contact es-cluster-2 during discovery and recognize it as the existing master.\n\nWhen elasticsearch-0 sends a join request to es-cluster-2, it should be accepted as a new member. The trickier part is elasticsearch-1 and elasticsearch-2, which have old cluster state from a previous version—they might try to elect a new master using that outdated voting configuration. However, in ES 8.x, nodes with stale cluster state should defer to the master when they contact it, so the discovery protocol should handle this correctly. The key is that the elasticsearch pods would actually be discovering the existing master through the seed hosts. When elasticsearch-1 and elasticsearch-2 rejoin and discover the existing master, they'll send join requests that get accepted, and the cluster state will update to reflect the new membership, including the voting configuration. This should resolve the issue, so I'll go ahead and update the ConfigMap.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":3002,"cache_read_input_tokens":149050,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":3002},"output_tokens":22,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"diagnostics":null,"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"82476b60-f4cb-48ca-92a0-0e5d08c71292","uuid":"1e303de1-55b0-4ab9-b70d-034b9062fd85","request_id":"req_011CcQjHKsh5y5LkyepDFJvz"}
